Abortion has been illegal in Lebanon since before the country’s independence, and the country went on to ratify both the International Convention on Civil and Political Rights and the International Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women, which explicitly outlaws abortion, except to save the life of the mother or to prevent grave damage to the mother’s physical or mental health [2]. Detailed legislation has been included in the Penal Code of 1943.

Lebanon’s Criminal Code states that “[a]nyone who practices any of the following acts: abortion; contraception; use of any invasive or non-invasive means such as hormone treatment, general anesthesia or topical anesthesia or any other procedure inducing contraception, will be sentenced to a prison term from one month to one year if the child is stillborn (...) and if the child is born, a prison term from one week to five years”.

Furthermore, if the outcome of the procedure is to “deprive society of the birth of an able and honest citizen, the sentence shall be from two weeks to two years”, and in the case that the procedure is to “starve the society of a human source”, a punishment of no longer than three years may be imposed [3]. Additionally, serious health consequences may result from harsh, traumatic complications.
